#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
MKT Christ — 1 Kings chapters 8–9 (fill: verse-sparse chapters)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-1kings-fill-8-9.py

Covers missing verses:
  ch 8: v11, v27, v30 exist; fills v1–10, v12–26, v28–29, v31–66  (63 missing)
  ch 9: v7 exists; fills v1–6, v8–28  (27 missing)

Christological focus:
  - Temple as type of Christ's body (John 2:19-21)
  - Cloud/glory → Shekinah → Incarnation (John 1:14)
  - Solomon's intercession → Christ as high priest/mediator (Heb 7:25)
  - Covenant conditionality fulfilled in Christ (Gal 4:4; Heb 10:5-10)
  - Canaanite permanent labor → Christ ransoming from bondage (Gal 3:13)
"""

import json
from pathlib import Path

ROOT = Path(__file__).resolve().parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

ONE_KINGS_CHRIST = {
    "8": {
        "1": "<p><span class='christ-type'>Solomon assembles all Israel to Jerusalem to bring up the ark — the gathering of the whole community around the presence of God. Christ gathers a greater assembly: &#x201C;where two or three are gathered in my name, there am I among them&#x201D; (Matt 18:20). The ark-procession to the temple is the type whose antitype is Christ himself drawing the nations to himself (John 12:32).</span></p>",
        "2": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>The feast in the seventh month, the month of Ethanim (Tishri), coincides with the Festival of Booths/Tabernacles — the great harvest feast when Israel lived in temporary shelters recalling wilderness sojourn. John 7:2-10 records Jesus at the Festival of Tabernacles, identifying himself as the living water the feast symbolized (John 7:37-38). The dedication of the temple at Tabernacles creates the typological backdrop for Jesus&#x2019;s Tabernacles-season revelation of himself as the true water and light.</span></p>",
        "3": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>The priests carry the ark to its place — a priestly act of installation, of bringing the divine presence into the holy place. Christ enters the greater and more perfect tent &#x201C;not made with hands&#x201D; (Heb 9:11), installing not a wooden box containing the covenant but his own flesh as the new locus of divine-human meeting.</span></p>",
        "4": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>The ark of the LORD, the tent of meeting, and all the sacred vessels are brought up together. All the holy structures of the wilderness period converge at the temple — the mobility of the tabernacle succeeded by the permanence of the temple. Christ fulfills both poles: he is the tent (John 1:14, <i>eskēnōsen</i> — he pitched his tent/tabernacled) and the permanent dwelling (Col 2:9 — the fullness of deity dwells bodily in him).</span></p>",
        "5": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>Sacrifices too numerous to count as the ark is carried in — an expression of the abundance of Israel&#x2019;s worship at this supreme moment. Christ&#x2019;s one offering of himself (Heb 10:14) is the single sacrifice that ends the uncountable sacrificial multitude: &#x201C;by one sacrifice he has made perfect forever those who are being made holy.&#x201D;</span></p>",
        "6": "<p><span class='christ-type'>The priests bring the ark to the Most Holy Place (<i>debir</i>) under the wings of the cherubim. The ark of the covenant — with its mercy seat (<i>kapporet</i>) where blood was sprinkled on the Day of Atonement — enters the innermost sanctuary. Paul calls Christ <i>hilastērion</i> in Rom 3:25 — the mercy seat, the place of atonement. What the ark and its cover typified, Christ fulfills: God&#x2019;s presence meeting sinners through atoning blood in the holiest place.</span></p>",
        "7": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>The cherubim spread their wings over the ark, sheltering it. The cherubim mark the place of God&#x2019;s enthroned presence (Exod 25:22: &#x201C;there I will meet with you&#x201D;). Christ is the one in whom God meets humanity; the place &#x201C;between the cherubim&#x201D; is fulfilled in the incarnate Son in whom &#x201C;all the fullness of God was pleased to dwell&#x201D; (Col 1:19).</span></p>",
        "8": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>The poles of the ark extended so their tips were visible from the Holy Place — visible but not seen from outside. The divine presence is discernible to those who draw near, concealed from the casual observer. Jesus speaks in parables precisely for this reason: &#x201C;to you it has been given to know the secrets of the kingdom; to them it has not been given&#x201D; (Matt 13:11). Access to the presence requires drawing near, as the poles require entering the Holy Place to see them.</span></p>",
        "9": "<p><span class='christ-type'>The ark contained nothing except the two stone tablets from Horeb — the covenant law. The ark as the container of the law is a type of Christ as the embodiment of the law: &#x201C;Do not think I have come to abolish the Law — I have come to fulfill it&#x201D; (Matt 5:17). What the ark housed in stone, Christ internalized in flesh. Hebrews 10:7 quotes Ps 40:8: &#x201C;in the scroll of the book it is written of me — I delight to do your will, O my God; your law is within my heart.&#x201D;</span></p>",
        "10": "<p><span class='christ-type'>When the priests came out of the Holy Place, a cloud filled the house of the LORD. The cloud is the <i>shekinah</i> — the visible manifestation of divine presence (the pillar of cloud in the wilderness, Exod 40:34-38). John 1:14: &#x201C;The Word became flesh and <i>eskēnōsen</i> among us, and we beheld his glory.&#x201D; The cloud-filled temple is the OT form of what the Incarnation fulfills: God&#x2019;s glory dwelling among his people in visible, tangible presence.</span></p>",
        "12": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>Solomon declares: &#x201C;The LORD has declared he would dwell in thick darkness (<i>araphel</i>).&#x201D; The <i>araphel</i> — the dense cloud of divine presence (Exod 20:21; Deut 5:22) — is the inaccessible glory of God that no one can approach and live. But Christ makes the inaccessible accessible: &#x201C;No one has ever seen God; the only Son, who is at the Father&#x2019;s side, has made him known&#x201D; (John 1:18). The thick darkness is pierced by the light of the incarnate Word.</span></p>",
        "13": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>Solomon has built an &#x201C;exalted house (<i>beit zebul</i>) — a permanent dwelling place.&#x201D; The temple is intended as a permanent habitation. But Jesus declared the greater permanence: &#x201C;Heaven and earth will pass away, but my words will not pass away&#x201D; (Matt 24:35). The temple Solomon built was destroyed; the dwelling Christ establishes — in the hearts of believers by the Spirit (1 Cor 3:16; 6:19) — is the permanent fulfillment the temple foreshadowed.</span></p>",
        "14": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>The king turns and blesses the whole assembly — a priestly-royal act of benediction. Christ blesses his disciples as he ascends (Luke 24:50-51) — the final act of the incarnate Lord as he departs is a gesture of blessing toward his people. Solomon&#x2019;s blessing of the assembly before the temple is a type of the ascending Christ&#x2019;s benediction before the heavenly sanctuary.</span></p>",
        "15": "<p><span class='christ-theme'>Solomon blesses the LORD who &#x201C;spoke with his own mouth to my father David and fulfilled it with his own hand.&#x201D; The pattern of divine word → divine fulfillment runs through all Scripture and finds its climax in Christ, who is himself the Word (John 1:1) that God spoke and fulfilled simultaneously. Every promise made through the prophets is &#x201C;Yes&#x201D; in him (2 Cor 1:20).</span></p>",
        "16": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>God chose no city among the tribes for a house — but he chose David. The election of a person (David) over a place precedes and shapes the election of a place (Jerusalem). The NT sharpens this: God has chosen a person, not primarily a place — &#x201C;you are a royal priesthood&#x201D; gathered around the risen Christ, not a building (1 Pet 2:9). The final form of God&#x2019;s presence is not in Jerusalem&#x2019;s stones but in the living community gathered around Christ.</span></p>",
        "17": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>It was in David&#x2019;s heart to build a house for the LORD&#x2019;s name. The desire was good, though David was not the appointed builder. The longing for God&#x2019;s dwelling among his people is the deep current of OT piety — from the tabernacle to the temple to the prophetic hope (Ezek 48:35: &#x201C;The LORD is There&#x201D;). Christ is the fullest answer to David&#x2019;s desire: &#x201C;The Word became flesh and dwelt among us.&#x201D;</span></p>",
        "18": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>God affirmed David&#x2019;s desire: &#x201C;You did well to have it in your heart.&#x201D; The desire for God&#x2019;s presence and glory is itself honored, even when the form of fulfillment differs from what was imagined. Christ honors the genuine longing of all OT worship: &#x201C;Your father Abraham rejoiced that he would see my day — he saw it and was glad&#x201D; (John 8:56). The temple-longing David felt was longing for Christ, though he did not yet know the name.</span></p>",
        "19": "<p><span class='christ-type'>David shall not build — &#x201C;your son shall build the house for my name.&#x201D; The Son builds what the Father prepared: the Davidic Son (Solomon) builds the earthly temple; the eternal Son (Christ) builds the heavenly and spiritual temple. Heb 3:3-6: &#x201C;Moses was faithful as a servant in all God&#x2019;s house, but Christ is faithful as a son over God&#x2019;s house. And we are his house.&#x201D;</span></p>",
        "20": "<p><span class='christ-theme'>The LORD has kept the promise — Solomon sits on David&#x2019;s throne and has built the temple. Fulfilled promise is the grammar of redemptive history; each fulfillment points toward and is surpassed by the final fulfillment in Christ. The throne David held and Solomon inherited finds its ultimate occupant in the one of whom Gabriel says: &#x201C;The Lord God will give him the throne of his father David, and he will reign over the house of Jacob forever&#x201D; (Luke 1:32-33).</span></p>",
        "21": "<p><span class='christ-type'>Solomon has provided a place for the ark — the covenant between God and Israel now has a permanent dwelling. Christ is the new covenant&#x2019;s dwelling; Heb 9:15 calls him &#x201C;the mediator of a new covenant.&#x201D; The ark housed the old covenant tablets; Christ inaugurates the new covenant in his blood (Luke 22:20), and the law is now written on hearts (Jer 31:33; Heb 10:16) rather than stone.</span></p>",
        "22": "<p><span class='christ-type'>Solomon stands before the altar of the LORD before the whole assembly, hands spread toward heaven — the posture of priestly intercession. The high-priestly prayer in John 17 is the NT parallel: Jesus &#x201C;lifted up his eyes to heaven&#x201D; (John 17:1) and interceded for his people before the cross. Solomon&#x2019;s posture of intercession is the type; Christ&#x2019;s eternal intercession (Heb 7:25 — &#x201C;he always lives to make intercession for them&#x201D;) is the antitype.</span></p>",
        "23": "<p><span class='christ-theme'>&#x201C;There is no God like you in heaven above or on earth below — you keep covenant and steadfast love (<i>hesed</i>) for your servants.&#x201D; The incomparability of YHWH (there is no God like him) is the ground of all intercession. In Christ, this incomparable God becomes personally present among his people: &#x201C;For in him all the fullness of God was pleased to dwell&#x201D; (Col 1:19). The <i>hesed</i> that is God&#x2019;s character is enacted in Christ&#x2019;s incarnation, death, and resurrection.</span></p>",
        "24": "<p><span class='christ-theme'>The prayer grounds itself in fulfilled promise: &#x201C;What you spoke with your mouth you have fulfilled with your hand.&#x201D; The pattern of divine speech → divine action reaches its apex in Christ who is both Word and Act — the speaking and the fulfilling are one person: &#x201C;Long ago God spoke to our fathers by the prophets… but in these last days he has spoken to us by his Son&#x201D; (Heb 1:1-2).</span></p>",
        "25": "<p><span class='christ-type'>The conditional promise to David: &#x201C;You shall never lack a man to sit before me on the throne of Israel — if only your sons walk before me.&#x201D; The conditionality of the Davidic promise (&#x201C;if only&#x201D;) is the problem Christ solves by obeying perfectly. Christ is the one Davidic descendant who walks before God with perfect integrity — the one who fulfills the condition the dynasty perpetually failed to meet. He is the promised king who sits on David&#x2019;s throne not by hereditary succession alone but by personal righteousness.</span></p>",
        "26": "<p><span class='christ-theme'>&#x201C;Let the word you spoke to your servant David be fulfilled.&#x201D; Solomon prays for fulfillment of the Davidic covenant. The ultimate fulfillment is not the stone temple or any Davidic king before the exile, but Christ — the eternal Son enthroned at God&#x2019;s right hand (Ps 110:1; Acts 2:34-36; Heb 1:13). Every prayer for Davidic covenant fulfillment in the OT is a prayer — knowingly or not — for the coming of Jesus.</span></p>",
        "28": "<p><span class='christ-type'>Solomon&#x2019;s plea: &#x201C;Give attention to your servant&#x2019;s prayer and plea, O LORD, and listen to the cry and the prayer your servant brings before you today.&#x201D; The great priestly prayer. Heb 5:7: &#x201C;In the days of his flesh, Jesus offered up prayers and supplications, with loud cries and tears, to him who was able to save him from death.&#x201D; Solomon&#x2019;s prayer to the God who dwells in heaven is the type of Christ&#x2019;s high-priestly intercession from the place of humiliation to the Father&#x2019;s throne.</span></p>",
        "29": "<p><span class='christ-type'>The prayer asks that God&#x2019;s eyes be open toward &#x201C;this house night and day — the place where you have said your name will dwell.&#x201D; The <i>name-theology</i> of the temple (God&#x2019;s name dwelling there, not God&#x2019;s person in a contained way) prepares for Christ: &#x201C;God has highly exalted him and bestowed on him the name that is above every name&#x201D; (Phil 2:9). The divine name that dwelt in the temple now dwells in and as the person of the Son.</span></p>",
        "31": "<p><span class='christ-type'>The first petition: when someone sins against a neighbor and takes an oath at the altar, God will judge and vindicate. The altar as the locus of covenant oath and divine judgment is the type of Christ as the place where sin is adjudicated. At the cross, God both &#x201C;condemns the guilty by bringing his deed on his own head&#x201D; (v32 — justice) and &#x201C;vindicates the innocent by rewarding his righteousness&#x201D; (v32 — grace). The cross is where both movements of v31-32 are fulfilled simultaneously.</span></p>",
        "32": "<p><span class='christ-direct'>&#x201C;Condemn the guilty by bringing his deed on his own head, and vindicate the innocent by rewarding his righteousness.&#x201D; At the cross, this double movement occurs: Christ the innocent is condemned, bearing guilty humanity&#x2019;s deeds on his own head (2 Cor 5:21: &#x201C;he made him to be sin who knew no sin&#x201D;); and sinners are vindicated in Christ&#x2019;s righteousness (Rom 5:18-19). The temple petition for just judgment is fulfilled at Calvary in inverted form: the innocent dies for the guilty so the guilty may be vindicated.</span></p>",
        "33": "<p><span class='christ-type'>The second petition: when Israel is defeated by an enemy because of sin, if they turn back, confess God&#x2019;s name, and pray toward this place, hear and forgive. The temple as the place of repentance-and-return establishes the pattern Christ fulfills: he is the place (John 2:21) to which all repentance is directed, the one in whose name forgiveness is declared (Acts 2:38; 4:12). Every OT prayer &#x201C;toward this house&#x201D; is, in retrospect, prayer toward Christ.</span></p>",
        "34": "<p><span class='christ-theme'>&#x201C;Forgive the sin of your people Israel and bring them back to the land.&#x201D; The petition pairs forgiveness and restoration — the double gift. Christ gives both: forgiveness of sins (Col 1:14) and the greater restoration, not to a piece of land, but to the new creation (2 Cor 5:17; Rev 21-22). The land promised to the fathers is a type whose ultimate antitype is the renewed cosmos &#x201C;in which righteousness dwells&#x201D; (2 Pet 3:13).</span></p>",
        "35": "<p><span class='christ-type'>Third petition: when there is no rain because of sin, if the people pray toward this place and turn from sin, hear and forgive. Drought as covenant curse (Deut 28:23-24) → prayer → forgiveness → rain. Christ is the living water (John 4:10; 7:37-38) who ends the deepest drought: &#x201C;Whoever drinks of the water I will give him will never be thirsty again.&#x201D; The rain for which Israel prays is a type of the Spirit Christ pours out (John 7:39; Acts 2:17-18).</span></p>",
        "36": "<p><span class='christ-theme'>&#x201C;Teach them the right way to walk (<i>ha-derekh ha-tovah</i>) and send rain.&#x201D; The connection between instruction in the right way and blessing resonates with Christ as the Way (John 14:6): he does not merely point to the right way — he is it. The Spirit sent by the risen Christ is both the teacher (John 14:26: &#x201C;he will teach you all things&#x201D;) and the one who brings the blessing of new life (Titus 3:5-6).</span></p>",
        "37": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>Fourth petition covers multiple disasters: famine, pestilence, blight, locusts, enemies besieging cities — the full range of covenant curse (Deut 28). The catalog of afflictions is the backdrop against which Christ&#x2019;s liberating work stands out. He heals, casts out demons, stills storms, raises the dead — confronting each category of affliction directly in his ministry, demonstrating the arrival of the kingdom that reverses curse.</span></p>",
        "38": "<p><span class='christ-type'>&#x201C;Whatever prayer or plea is made by any person or by all your people Israel — each knowing the affliction of his own heart.&#x201D; The phrase <i>makkah levavo</i> (the plague/affliction of his own heart) acknowledges that the deepest human wound is interior — sin within. The petition recognizes that external circumstances (famine, plague) are secondary to the inner corruption that generates them. Christ addresses this root: &#x201C;For out of the heart come evil thoughts&#x201D; (Matt 15:19) — and Christ cleanses the heart (Acts 15:9: &#x201C;cleansing their hearts by faith&#x201D;).</span></p>",
        "39": "<p><span class='christ-type'>&#x201C;Give to each person according to his ways, whose heart you know — for you alone know the hearts of all the children of mankind.&#x201D; God as the heart-knower (<i>yode'a levavot</i>) is affirmed. Christ, in his divine nature, knows what is in humans (John 2:24-25: &#x201C;he knew all people — he knew what was in man&#x201D;) — the same divine attribute. The prayer&#x2019;s theological claim about God&#x2019;s omniscience is a description of Christ&#x2019;s nature recognized only in retrospect from the NT.</span></p>",
        "40": "<p><span class='christ-theme'>&#x201C;So that they may fear you all the days they live in the land.&#x201D; The goal of all divine response to prayer is covenant fear — the reverence that is the beginning of wisdom (Prov 1:7). Christ both embodies this fear (Heb 5:7: &#x201C;because of his reverent submission he was heard&#x201D;) and produces it in his people through the Spirit: &#x201C;I will put my Spirit within you and cause you to walk in my statutes&#x201D; (Ezek 36:27).</span></p>",
        "41": "<p><span class='christ-direct'>Fifth petition: &#x201C;Moreover, when a foreigner — someone not of your people Israel — comes from a distant land because of your name.&#x201D; The inclusion of the <i>nokri</i> (foreigner) in Solomon&#x2019;s prayer is remarkable — the temple is intended from its dedication as a house of prayer for all peoples. Jesus quotes this petition directly in cleansing the temple: &#x201C;My house shall be called a house of prayer for all nations&#x201D; (Mark 11:17, citing Isa 56:7). Christ&#x2019;s indignation at the money changers is precisely because they excluded the Gentiles from the outer court where they should have been praying.</span></p>",
        "42": "<p><span class='christ-theme'>The foreigner comes &#x201C;because of your great name and your mighty, outstretched arm.&#x201D; The name and the powerful acts that undergird it draw the nations. In the NT, it is the name of Jesus that draws the Gentiles: &#x201C;in his name the nations will hope&#x201D; (Matt 12:21, citing Isa 42:4). The outstretched arm — the Exodus image of divine deliverance — is enacted in the resurrection and exaltation of Christ, the ultimate mighty act that draws all nations.</span></p>",
        "43": "<p><span class='christ-direct'>&#x201C;Hear in heaven your dwelling place and grant everything for which the foreigner prays — so that all peoples of the earth may know your name.&#x201D; The purpose: all peoples knowing God&#x2019;s name. The Great Commission is the NT form of this purpose: &#x201C;Go therefore and make disciples of all nations… teaching them to observe all that I have commanded you&#x201D; (Matt 28:19-20). Solomon&#x2019;s prayer for the nations reaching God through the temple finds its fulfillment in the nations reaching God through Christ, the true temple.</span></p>",
        "44": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>Sixth petition: when Israel goes to war, if they pray toward Jerusalem and the temple, hear and uphold their cause. The warrior-prayer toward the holy city is the type of intercession in the name of Christ: &#x201C;Whatever you ask in my name, this I will do, so that the Father may be glorified in the Son&#x201D; (John 14:13). Prayer &#x201C;toward this house&#x201D; has become prayer &#x201C;in this name&#x201D; — the place replaced by the person.</span></p>",
        "45": "<p><span class='christ-theme'>&#x201C;Hear their prayer and plea in heaven and uphold their cause (<i>mishpat</i>).&#x201D; The word <i>mishpat</i> (justice/cause) points to divine advocacy. Christ is the believer&#x2019;s advocate (<i>paraklētos</i> — 1 John 2:1): &#x201C;If anyone sins, we have an advocate with the Father, Jesus Christ the righteous one.&#x201D; His intercession in heaven upholds the cause of his people before the divine tribunal.</span></p>",
        "46": "<p><span class='christ-direct'>Seventh and climactic petition: &#x201C;If they sin against you — for there is no one who does not sin (<i>ki ein adam asher lo yecheta</i>).&#x201D; The universal sinfulness that makes the seventh petition necessary is the theological premise of the gospel. Paul grounds the doctrine in this universal reality (Rom 3:23: &#x201C;all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God&#x201D;) and in Solomon&#x2019;s assertion (Eccl 7:20). Christ alone is the exception — the one human who does not sin (Heb 4:15) — and therefore the only possible mediator for those who do.</span></p>",
        "47": "<p><span class='christ-type'>In exile, if the people &#x201C;come to their senses and repent&#x201D; (<i>shavu el-libam</i> — return to their hearts) and pray. The prodigal son&#x2019;s &#x201C;he came to himself&#x201D; (Luke 15:17) is the NT parallel: <i>eis heauton de elthōn</i> — coming to himself. The pattern of exile-repentance-return that Solomon prays for is the pattern Christ enacts in the parable and in salvation: the far country, the coming to oneself, the return to the Father who runs to meet the returning one.</span></p>",
        "48": "<p><span class='christ-type'>&#x201C;If they return to you with all their heart and soul in the land of their enemies.&#x201D; Whole-hearted return from captivity is what Deuteronomy promises (Deut 30:1-10) and what the new covenant effects: &#x201C;I will circumcise your heart and the heart of your offspring, so that you will love the LORD your God with all your heart and with all your soul&#x201D; (Deut 30:6). The return &#x201C;with all their heart&#x201D; is not achievable by command alone — it requires the Spirit&#x2019;s work (Ezek 36:26-27), which Christ sends (John 16:7).</span></p>",
        "49": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>&#x201C;Hear their prayer and plea from heaven.&#x201D; The upward movement of the prayer — from the land of captivity, through the direction of Jerusalem, to heaven — mirrors the ascending mediatorial structure of Christ&#x2019;s intercession. Heb 7:25: &#x201C;He is able to save to the uttermost those who draw near to God through him, since he always lives to make intercession for them.&#x201D; The prayer heard from earth to heaven, and the answer flowing from heaven to earth, is the shape of all Christian prayer in Christ&#x2019;s name.</span></p>",
        "50": "<p><span class='christ-type'>&#x201C;Forgive your people who have sinned against you and all their transgressions, and move their captors to show them compassion.&#x201D; The double request — forgiveness from God and compassion from enemies — corresponds to the double work of the gospel: vertical reconciliation (forgiveness) and horizontal reconciliation (enemies becoming neighbors). Eph 2:14-16: Christ &#x201C;has made us both one and has broken down the dividing wall of hostility… reconciling us both to God in one body through the cross.&#x201D;</span></p>",
        "51": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>&#x201C;For they are your people, your own inheritance, whom you brought out of Egypt, out of that iron-smelting furnace.&#x201D; Israel as God&#x2019;s possession (<i>nachalah</i>) brought from the furnace of Egypt — the Exodus as the paradigm of redemption. Christ enacts the new Exodus (Luke 9:31 — Moses and Elijah speak of his <i>exodon</i>) bringing a people out of a greater bondage: &#x201C;He has delivered us from the domain of darkness and transferred us to the kingdom of his beloved Son&#x201D; (Col 1:13).</span></p>",
        "52": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>&#x201C;May your eyes be open to your servant&#x2019;s plea and to your people Israel&#x2019;s plea, listening whenever they call on you.&#x201D; The final petition of Solomon&#x2019;s prayer: continual divine attentiveness to prayer. Christ ensures this: &#x201C;Ask and it will be given to you… For everyone who asks receives&#x201D; (Matt 7:7-8). The open divine eye Solomon prays for is guaranteed in Christ&#x2019;s name: &#x201C;Whatever you ask the Father in my name, he will give it to you&#x201D; (John 16:23).</span></p>",
        "53": "<p><span class='christ-theme'>&#x201C;For you separated them from all the peoples of the earth to be your inheritance, as you declared through your servant Moses.&#x201D; Israel&#x2019;s election as God&#x2019;s separated people (<i>hivdaltem</i>) is the basis of the prayer. The NT widens the circle of the separated people: &#x201C;You are a chosen race, a royal priesthood, a holy nation, a people for his own possession&#x201D; (1 Pet 2:9 — addressed to Gentile believers). What was Israel by ethnic-covenantal identity, the church becomes through union with Christ.</span></p>",
        "54": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>When Solomon finished praying, he rose from kneeling before the altar with hands spread toward heaven. The bodily posture of prayer — kneeling, hands spread — mirrors what the Psalms prescribe and what Christ himself embodied: &#x201C;Falling on his face he prayed&#x201D; (Matt 26:39). Solomon&#x2019;s prayer-posture is the human posture before the divine; Christ&#x2019;s prayer in Gethsemane is the perfect enactment of that posture in the face of the cross.</span></p>",
        "55": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>Solomon stood and blessed the whole assembly with a loud voice — the benedictory act after the completion of the great prayer. The risen Christ&#x2019;s final act before ascension is blessing: &#x201C;While he blessed them, he parted from them and was carried up into heaven&#x201D; (Luke 24:51). The temple dedication ends in blessing; the new covenant begins with the same.</span></p>",
        "56": "<p><span class='christ-theme'>&#x201C;Blessed be the LORD, who has given rest to his people Israel in keeping with all his promises. Not one word has fallen to the ground.&#x201D; The fulfillment of every divine word is the note Solomon strikes at the dedication. Heb 4:8-10 develops the rest-theme: Joshua gave temporary rest; Christ gives the ultimate Sabbath rest. And 2 Cor 1:20: &#x201C;All the promises of God find their Yes in him&#x201D; — the not-one-word-fallen principle reaches its ultimate affirmation in Christ.</span></p>",
        "57": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>&#x201C;May the LORD our God be with us as he was with our fathers. May he never abandon or forsake us.&#x201D; The petition &#x201C;do not forsake us&#x201D; (<i>al-ya'azvenu</i>) is answered definitively in Christ: &#x201C;I am with you always, to the end of the age&#x201D; (Matt 28:20). The Emmanuel promise (Isa 7:14; Matt 1:23 — God with us) ensures what Solomon prayed for: permanent, unbreakable divine presence with his people through the Spirit (John 14:16-17).</span></p>",
        "58": "<p><span class='christ-type'>&#x201C;That he may incline our hearts toward him, to walk in all his ways.&#x201D; The prayer acknowledges the need for God to incline (<i>lehattot</i>) the human heart — it does not incline itself toward God. This is the doctrine of sovereign grace: the new covenant fulfills this prayer through the Spirit. Ezek 36:26-27: &#x201C;I will give you a new heart&#x201D; — and Christ sends the Spirit who produces this inclination (Phil 2:13: &#x201C;for it is God who works in you, both to will and to work for his good pleasure&#x201D;).</span></p>",
        "59": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>&#x201C;May these words of mine with which I have prayed before the LORD remain near to the LORD our God day and night.&#x201D; Solomon prays that his prayer not be forgotten but remain before God perpetually. Christ lives to make perpetual intercession (Heb 7:25) — his prayers are not completed and forgotten but ongoing, continuous advocacy. The &#x201C;day and night&#x201D; presence of prayer before God that Solomon requests is what Christ&#x2019;s eternal intercession guarantees.</span></p>",
        "60": "<p><span class='christ-theme'>&#x201C;So that all the peoples of the earth may know that the LORD is God — there is no other.&#x201D; The universal scope of Israel&#x2019;s mission climaxes here: the temple is built not for Israel alone but so that all nations might know the only God. Christ commissions his disciples to this same universal task: &#x201C;Go therefore and make disciples of all nations&#x201D; (Matt 28:19). The monotheistic proclamation &#x201C;there is no other&#x201D; is the theological foundation of both the Shema and the gospel.</span></p>",
        "61": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>&#x201C;May your heart be wholly devoted to the LORD our God.&#x201D; The exhortation to wholehearted devotion is the Deuteronomic ideal (Deut 6:5) — the first and greatest commandment. Jesus cites it as such (Mark 12:30). The church is called to this by the Spirit — and Christ alone has perfectly lived the whole-hearted devotion that he commands. His perfect love of God is the foundation on which our imperfect love is accepted.</span></p>",
        "62": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>The king and all Israel offered sacrifices before the LORD — the congregation joins in the priestly work of the dedication. The final book of Revelation shows the consummation of this: the redeemed from every nation worship before the throne (Rev 7:9-10). Solomon&#x2019;s assembly offering sacrifices is the OT form of the great eschatological assembly worshiping the Lamb who was slain.</span></p>",
        "63": "<p><span class='christ-type'>Solomon offered 22,000 oxen and 120,000 sheep as peace offerings (<i>shelamim</i>) — the vast scale expressing the magnitude of dedication. The sheer number of sacrifices shows the inadequacy of animal sacrifice to finally accomplish what it points to: Heb 10:4, &#x201C;for it is impossible for the blood of bulls and goats to take away sins.&#x201D; The 142,000 animals offered at the temple dedication are a down-payment on the one sacrifice Christ makes that does what all the others could not.</span></p>",
        "64": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>Solomon consecrates the middle of the court because the bronze altar was too small for all the offerings. The altar&#x2019;s inadequacy — too small for the volume of worship — is an inadvertent parable: all the altars of the OT were too small for the sacrifice God required. The cross alone is the altar large enough, the place where the offering is finally adequate. Heb 13:10: &#x201C;We have an altar from which those who serve the tent have no right to eat.&#x201D;</span></p>",
        "65": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>The feast extends seven days, then seven more — a fourteen-day celebration from Lebo-hamath (the northern extent) to the Brook of Egypt (the southern). The geographic scope of the assembled worshipers (all of Israel from north to south) anticipates the universal scope of the new covenant community, gathered &#x201C;from every tribe and language and people and nation&#x201D; (Rev 5:9).</span></p>",
        "66": "<p><span class='christ-theme'>The people bless the king and return home &#x201C;full of joy and gladness for all the goodness the LORD had shown to his servant David and to his people Israel.&#x201D; Joy and gladness (<i>simchah ve-tov lev</i>) are the covenant blessings of the festive assembly. The NT form: the disciples return to Jerusalem with great joy after Christ&#x2019;s ascension (Luke 24:52); the early church ate together with &#x201C;glad and generous hearts&#x201D; (Acts 2:46). The dedication joy is a type of the post-resurrection, Spirit-given joy of those who know God has kept his greatest promise.</span></p>"
    },
    "9": {
        "1": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>&#x201C;When Solomon had finished building the house of the LORD and the royal palace and all he desired to build.&#x201D; The completion of the building project marks a moment of apparent fullness — everything done, everything built. But the conditional that follows (vv4-9) shows that physical completion is not the final word. Christ brings the ultimate completion: &#x201C;It is finished&#x201D; (<i>tetelestai</i> — John 19:30) — not the completion of a building but the completion of the redemptive work the temple symbolized.</span></p>",
        "2": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>The LORD appeared to Solomon a second time, as at Gibeon. The two divine appearances to Solomon bookend the temple project — before (ch3, the wisdom gift) and after (ch9, the conditional covenant). Christ&#x2019;s pattern similarly brackets his ministry: baptism (theophany with the Father&#x2019;s voice — Matt 3:17) and transfiguration (theophany with Moses, Elijah, and the Father&#x2019;s voice — Matt 17:5). Divine appearances at the key transitional moments of the work.</span></p>",
        "3": "<p><span class='christ-type'>&#x201C;I have heard your prayer and your plea. I have consecrated this house by putting my name there forever.&#x201D; God&#x2019;s name dwelling in the temple forever — the <i>le-olam</i> (forever) claim is conditional (v4-9 immediately qualifies it). Christ is the true and unconditional forever-dwelling of the divine name: the name above every name (Phil 2:9) dwells in him bodily and permanently, without the conditionality that makes Solomon&#x2019;s temple vulnerable to withdrawal.</span></p>",
        "4": "<p><span class='christ-type'>&#x201C;As for you, if you walk before me as your father David walked — with integrity (<i>tom</i>) and uprightness (<i>yosher</i>), doing all I commanded you and keeping my statutes.&#x201D; The condition laid on the Davidic king is perfect covenant obedience. No historical Davidic king fully met this condition. Christ alone walks before the Father with complete integrity and uprightness — &#x201C;holy, innocent, unstained, separated from sinners&#x201D; (Heb 7:26). He is the one Davidic descendant who actually satisfies the covenant condition.</span></p>",
        "5": "<p><span class='christ-direct'>&#x201C;Then I will establish your royal throne over Israel forever (<i>le-olam</i>), as I promised David: you will never lack a man on the throne.&#x201D; The forever-throne is promised on condition. Christ inherits this promise without condition because he meets the condition perfectly: &#x201C;Of the increase of his government and of peace there will be no end, on the throne of David and over his kingdom, to establish it and to uphold it with justice and righteousness from this time forth and forevermore&#x201D; (Isa 9:7). The &#x201C;forever&#x201D; that was conditional for Solomon is unconditional for Christ.</span></p>",
        "6": "<p><span class='christ-type'>&#x201C;But if you or your children turn away from following me and do not keep my commandments and statutes I have placed before you, and go and serve other gods and worship them.&#x201D; The &#x201C;if&#x201D; of apostasy becomes the &#x201C;then&#x201D; of exile (v7). Christ guarantees against this: his new covenant people are given hearts that do not turn away (Jer 32:40: &#x201C;I will put the fear of me in their hearts, that they may not turn from me&#x201D;). The conditionality of the Sinai/Davidic covenant is overcome by the new covenant&#x2019;s gift of faithfulness.</span></p>",
        "8": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>&#x201C;This exalted house will become a ruin. Everyone who passes by will be appalled and will hiss, saying, Why has the LORD done this to this land and to this house?&#x201D; The destruction of the temple that God here forewarns was fulfilled in 586 BC (Babylonian) and AD 70 (Roman). Jesus explicitly predicts the latter: &#x201C;Do you see these great buildings? There will not be left here one stone upon another that will not be thrown down&#x201D; (Mark 13:2). Christ&#x2019;s prediction of AD 70 aligns with God&#x2019;s warning in ch9 — the conditional covenant runs its course.</span></p>",
        "9": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>&#x201C;Because they abandoned the LORD their God who brought their fathers out of Egypt, and took hold of other gods, worshiping and serving them — therefore the LORD has brought all this disaster on them.&#x201D; The logic of covenant discipline: abandonment of YHWH → divine abandonment of Israel. Christ quotes this logic in his lament over Jerusalem (Matt 23:37-38: &#x201C;How often I wanted to gather your children… Look, your house is left to you desolate&#x201D;). The prophetic pattern of rejection → desolation reaches its NT fulfillment in AD 70.</span></p>",
        "10": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>Twenty years to build the two houses — the LORD&#x2019;s house and the palace. The equal weighting of the two projects (temple and palace) throughout 1 Kings reflects the entanglement of royal power and sacred space in Israel. Christ separates them definitively: &#x201C;My kingdom is not of this world&#x201D; (John 18:36). The sacred and the political are not synonymous in the kingdom he establishes — a clarification the OT monarchy never fully achieved.</span></p>",
        "11": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>Solomon gives Hiram twenty cities in Galilee in payment for timber and gold. The Galilee region — later called &#x201C;Galilee of the nations&#x201D; (Isa 9:1) — is the territory Solomon gives to a Gentile king. Matthew 4:15-16 quotes Isaiah 9:1-2 to frame Jesus&#x2019;s Galilean ministry: the light dawns precisely in the territory Solomon ceded to Hiram. The land given to the Gentile becomes the land where the Light of the World begins his ministry.</span></p>",
        "12": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>Hiram inspects the cities and is displeased — he calls them &#x201C;Cabul&#x201D; (a name meaning &#x201C;as nothing&#x201D; or &#x201C;good for nothing&#x201D;). The exchange that seemed adequate on paper disappoints in person. The temple project comes at high human and political cost. Christ warned his disciples about the cost of the kingdom: &#x201C;Count the cost&#x201D; (Luke 14:28-30). What appears to be adequate provision from outside often reveals itself as insufficient when examined up close.</span></p>",
        "13": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>&#x201C;What are these towns you have given me, my brother?&#x201D; — and they are called Cabul. The diplomatic disappointment between Solomon and Hiram echoes the larger theme of human alliance&#x2019;s inadequacy. The nations that Solomon courts — Egypt, Tyre — will ultimately prove unreliable. Christ offers a relationship that does not disappoint: &#x201C;Come to me, all who are weary and burdened, and I will give you rest&#x201D; (Matt 11:28). The Hiram-Cabul exchange is a minor chord in the Solomonic narrative&#x2019;s broader theme of failed human partnership.</span></p>",
        "14": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>Hiram sent 120 talents of gold. The gold flows toward the temple-building project — the nations&#x2019; wealth contributing to God&#x2019;s house. The eschatological vision of the prophets sees this pattern completed: &#x201C;The wealth of the nations shall come to you&#x201D; (Isa 60:5). The temple&#x2019;s material richness is a type of the new Jerusalem where &#x201C;the kings of the earth will bring their glory into it&#x201D; (Rev 21:24).</span></p>",
        "15": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>The account of the forced labor used for Solomon&#x2019;s building projects — the Millo, the wall of Jerusalem, Hazor, Megiddo, Gezer. The administrative and military infrastructure of the empire is built on conscripted labor. Christ comes to set the burdened free: &#x201C;Come to me, all who labor and are heavy laden, and I will give you rest. Take my yoke upon you&#x201D; (Matt 11:28-29). The <i>mas</i> (forced labor) of Solomon&#x2019;s kingdom is the type of the human condition under sin; Christ&#x2019;s yoke is easy and his burden light.</span></p>",
        "16": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>Pharaoh captured and burned Gezer and gave it as a dowry to Solomon&#x2019;s wife. The Egyptian king destroys a Canaanite city and gives the ruins to his son-in-law. The Egyptian alliance — built on a marriage that Deuteronomy implicitly prohibits — produces this morally ambiguous gift. Christ&#x2019;s gifts to his bride (the church) are not the ruins of conquered cities but the inheritance of the Kingdom itself: &#x201C;Fear not, little flock, for it is your Father&#x2019;s good pleasure to give you the kingdom&#x201D; (Luke 12:32).</span></p>",
        "17": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>Solomon rebuilds Gezer and Lower Beth-horon. The pattern of building and rebuilding — reconstructing what was destroyed — runs through both Testaments. Christ&#x2019;s work is ultimately reconstruction: &#x201C;I will build my church&#x201D; (Matt 16:18) — building a community that cannot be destroyed, unlike the city of Gezer.</span></p>",
        "18": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>Baalath and Tamar in the wilderness — store cities built in remote areas to extend the administrative reach of Solomon&#x2019;s kingdom. The empire grows in every direction. Christ&#x2019;s kingdom also extends to wilderness places — &#x201C;Go therefore to the main roads and invite to the feast as many as you find&#x201D; (Matt 22:9). The reach of the kingdom goes to unexpected places.</span></p>",
        "19": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>All of Solomon&#x2019;s store cities, chariot cities, cavalry cities, and whatever he desired to build — the full extent of the imperial infrastructure. The military and commercial network is impressive, but vulnerable. Isaiah 31:1: &#x201C;Woe to those who go down to Egypt for help and rely on horses, who trust in chariots because they are many.&#x201D; The chariot cities of Solomon are the form of trust that the prophets will criticize. Christ calls to a different strength: &#x201C;blessed are the poor in spirit, for theirs is the kingdom&#x201D; (Matt 5:3).</span></p>",
        "20": "<p><span class='christ-type'>All the non-Israelite peoples remaining in the land — Amorites, Hittites, Perizzites, Hivites, Jebusites — Solomon conscripts as forced laborers. The Canaanite remnant serves as permanent slaves. This is the shadow side of the Conquest&#x2019;s incompleteness: what should have been destroyed became a permanent underclass. Christ&#x2019;s redemption includes those who were permanent outsiders: &#x201C;You who once were far off have been brought near by the blood of Christ&#x201D; (Eph 2:13). The Canaanite laborers are a figure of those the gospel reaches — once outsiders, now incorporated.</span></p>",
        "21": "<p><span class='christ-type'>Their descendants — those Israel had been unable to destroy — Solomon made into a forced labor corps (<i>mas-oved</i> — tributary forced labor) that continues to this day. The permanent Canaanite corvée is the OT form of bondage under the covenant&#x2019;s incompleteness. Gal 3:13: &#x201C;Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us.&#x201D; The bondage the Canaanites embodied (and that Israel would later experience in exile) is what Christ finally ends — not by destroying the enslaved but by absorbing the curse that justified the bondage.</span></p>",
        "22": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>But Solomon did not make Israelites into slaves — they served as soldiers, officials, commanders, captains, and cavalry. The distinction (Canaanite = slave, Israelite = soldier/officer) reflects the covenant distinction that Paul radicalizes in Christ: in Christ &#x201C;there is neither slave nor free&#x201D; (Gal 3:28). The ethnic and social stratification that organized Solomon&#x2019;s labor force is overcome in the body of Christ where all are &#x201C;one in Christ Jesus.&#x201D;</span></p>",
        "23": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>Five hundred and fifty chief officers over Solomon&#x2019;s workforce. The supervisory class between king and workers — the middle management of empire. Christ reorganizes authority: in his kingdom, the greatest is the servant of all (Mark 10:43-44). The hierarchical structure of Solomon&#x2019;s workforce is inverted in the kingdom where authority is exercised through service, not over subjects.</span></p>",
        "24": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>Pharaoh&#x2019;s daughter moves from the city of David into her own palace, and Solomon builds the Millo. The accommodation of the Egyptian princess — a constant background presence in the Solomonic narrative — signals the entanglement of pagan influence with the Israelite court. The gradual normalization of Pharaoh&#x2019;s daughter&#x2019;s presence anticipates Solomon&#x2019;s later marriage-induced apostasy (ch11). What is tolerated for political benefit becomes spiritually corrosive — a pattern Christ identifies: &#x201C;You cannot serve God and money&#x201D; (Matt 6:24).</span></p>",
        "25": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>Three times a year Solomon offered burnt and peace offerings on the altar — the annual liturgical cycle of Israel&#x2019;s three pilgrimage feasts (Passover, Pentecost, Tabernacles). The regular sacrificial round points to Christ, who offered himself &#x201C;once for all&#x201D; (Heb 7:27) — the once-and-forever sacrifice that the three-times-annual repetition anticipated. &#x201C;So he completed the house&#x201D; — the sacrificial work completed the temple&#x2019;s purpose; Christ&#x2019;s sacrifice completed the sacrificial system.</span></p>",
        "26": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>Solomon builds a fleet of ships at Ezion-geber on the Red Sea — the sea from which Israel had escaped Egypt (Exod 14-15). Now the same sea becomes a commercial highway. The reversal is striking: the sea of death (Egypt&#x2019;s army drowned) becomes the sea of trade and profit. Christ transforms death-places into life: the cross, the instrument of execution, becomes &#x201C;the power of God and the wisdom of God&#x201D; (1 Cor 1:24) — the symbol of death that generates life.</span></p>",
        "27": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>Hiram sends experienced sailors to serve alongside Solomon&#x2019;s men. Gentile expertise serving the Israelite king&#x2019;s purposes — a cooperation that produces great results (the Ophir expedition). The NT mission similarly draws on diverse gifts: &#x201C;There are varieties of gifts but the same Spirit&#x201D; (1 Cor 12:4). The nations contribute their excellence to the building of God&#x2019;s purposes — just as the Sidonians contribute their timber skill and Hiram&#x2019;s sailors contribute their seamanship.</span></p>",
        "28": "<p><span class='christ-shadow'>They bring back 420 talents of gold from Ophir. Gold flowing to Jerusalem from the ends of the earth — the type of the nations bringing their wealth and glory to God&#x2019;s city. Isaiah 60:6: &#x201C;They shall bring gold and frankincense, and shall proclaim the praise of the LORD.&#x201D; The Magi bringing gold to the infant Jesus (Matt 2:11) is the narrative fulfillment: the wealth of distant nations comes to the true king, recognized at last for who he is.</span></p>"
    }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', '1kings')
    merge_comm(existing, ONE_KINGS_CHRIST)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', '1kings', existing)
    from pathlib import Path as P2
    il = json.loads((ROOT / 'data/interlinear/1kings.json').read_text())
    all_ok = True
    for ch in ['8', '9']:
        got = set(existing.get(ch, {}).keys())
        need = set(il[ch].keys())
        missing = need - got
        if missing:
            print(f'  ch{ch} STILL MISSING: {sorted(missing, key=int)}')
            all_ok = False
        else:
            print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(got)} verses complete')
    if all_ok:
        print('1 Kings christ fill (chs 8–9) done. All verses present.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
